    @{"Edit commands...   " LINK Editcommands}

@endnode
@node "Find" "'Find...' window"

 The 'Find...' window can be used for find and replace functions.

The gadgets:

 @{u}Gadget         Function                                                    @{uu}
@{b} Find@{ub}           The string you want to find.
 @{b}Change To@{ub}      The string you want to replace the find-string with.
 @{b}Case sensitive@{ub}	Upper case is not the same as lower case ('a' != 'A').
 @{b}Whole words@{ub}    Only look for the find-string as a whole word.
 @{b}Use patterns@{ub}   When this options is selected AmisED will use the AmigaDOS
                pattern matching functions to find the pattern you entered
                in the find gadget. (See below for more information about
                AmigaDOS patterns).
 @{b}Find Next@{ub}      Find the next occurrence of the find-string in the text.
 @{b}Find Prev@{ub}      Find the previous occurrence of the find-string in the text.
 @{b}Repl Next@{ub}      Replace the string and find the next.
 @{b}Repl Prev@{ub}      Replace the string and find the previous.
 @{b}Replace All@{ub}    Replace all occurrences of the find-string in the text by the
                replace string.
 @{b}Cancel@{ub}         Close this window.

@{u}AmigaDOS patterns:@{uu}

        ?       Matches a single character.
        #       Matches the following expression 0 or more times.
        (ab|cd) Matches any one of the items seperated by '|'.
        ~       Negates the following expression.  It matches all strings
                that do not match the expression (aka ~(foo) matches all
                strings that are not exactly "foo").
        [abc]   Character class: matches any of the characters in the class.
        [~bc]   Character class: matches any of the characters not in the
                class.
        a-z     Character range (only within character classes). 
        %       Matches 0 characters always (useful in "(foo|bar|%)").
        *       Synonym for "#?", not available by default in 2.0.  Available
                as an option that can be turned on.

        "Expression" in the above table means either a single character
        (ex: "#?"), or an alternation (ex: "#(ab|cd|ef)"), or a character
        class (ex: "#[a-zA-Z]").

Sometimes you might have to use some tricks to find the things you want, for
example:

- searching for '(' becomes: [(]
- searching for ')' becomes: [)]
- searching for '[' becomes: [[]
- searching for ']' becomes: ~(~([\-^])|\|^)
                                ---> all that is not not '\',']' or '^' and
                                     not '\' or '^'.
                                     (ASCII: '\'=92  '['=93 and '^'=94).

- searching for '~' becomes: ~(~([a~])|a)
                                ---> all that is not not 'a' or '~' and not
                                     'a'.

Ofcource you can also switch of the use of patterns, then you can simple
search for ']' using ']'.   :-))

@endnode
@node "FindFunctions" "'Find functions...' window"

 The 'Find functions...' window can be used for some special find functions.
Built in there is a find function for AmigaGuide nodes. If you select this
one and then click on the 'Ok' button you will get a list of all AmigaGuide
nodes in the document you are editing. Other find functions can be added
with the 'Add' button. The find functions are GoldED compatible.

The gadgets:

 @{u}Gadget         Function                                                    @{uu}
 @{b}Ok@{ub}             Activate this find function.
 @{b}Add@{ub}            Add a find function.
 @{b}Remove@{ub}         Remove the selected find function.
 @{b}Cancel@{ub}         Close this window.

@endnode
@node "UndoList" "'Undo list...' window"

 The 'Undo list...' window shows the list of undo's that are still in the
undo buffer.

The gadgets:

 @{u}Gadget         Function                                                    @{uu}
 @{b}Undo@{ub}           Perform the LAST command in the undo list (normal Undo).

@endnode
@node "Macro" "'Macro...' window"

 The 'Macro...' window can be used the create and edit macro's.

The gadgets:

 @{u}Gadget         Function                                                    @{uu}
 @{b}Add@{ub}            Create a new macro (Name: 'New Macro').
 @{b}Remove@{ub}         Remove the selected macro.
 @{b}Move up@{ub}        Move the selected macro one place up in the list.
 @{b}Move down@{ub}      Move the selected macro one place down in the list.
 @{b}Play Macro@{ub}     Play the selected macro.
 @{b}Record@{ub}         Start or continue recording the selected macro.
 @{b}Stop recording@{ub}	Stop recording the macro.
 @{b}Edit@{ub}           Edit the selected macro, you will get an @{"Edit commands..." LINK Editcommands}
                window to do this.
 @{b}Short cut@{ub}      Assign a short-cut to the selected macro, you will get the
                '@{"Keyboard..." LINK Keyboard...}' window to do this (all you have to do is press
                the key / key-combination you want the macro to be assigned
                to.
 @{b}No short cut@{ub}   Remove the short-cut for the selected macro.
 @{b}Load@{ub}           Load a macro from disk.
 @{b}Save@{ub}           Save a macro to disk.

@endnode
@node "Information" "'Information...' window"

 The 'Information...' window gives you information about the text you are
editing.

 @{u}Gadget         Function                                                    @{uu}
 @{b}Name@{ub}           The name of the current document.
 @{b}Path@{ub}           The location where the current document is saved.
 @{b}Characters@{ub}     The amount of characters in the current document.
 @{b}Lines@{ub}          The amount of lines in the current document.
 @{b}Words@{ub}          The amount of words in the current document.
 @{b}( and )@{ub}        How many occurences of this character are present.
                Useful for C documents and installer scripts.
 @{b}Tab size@{ub}       Change the tab size for this text (the global tab size is
                defined in the '@{"Editor..." LINK Editor...}' window).
 @{b}Av. Length@{ub}     The average length of the lines in the current document.
 @{b}Av. Length@{ub}     The average length of the words in the current document.
 @{b}{ and }@{ub}        How many occurences of this character are present.
                Useful for C documents.
 @{b}Tooltypes@{ub}      Here you are able to change the tooltypes of the current
                document in the same manner as on the Workbench.
 @{b}Ok@{ub}             Close this window.
 @{b}Next@{ub}           Some information about the next document in memory.

@endnode
@node "About" "'About' window"

 The 'About' window shows information about the version and the makers of
the AmisED version you are using.

 @{u}Gadget         Function                                                    @{uu}
 @{b}Continue@{ub}       Close this window.
 @{b}More@{ub}           Show an other about window.

@endnode
@node "ProjectManager" "'Project Manager' window"

 The 'Project Manager' window can be used to create a list of files that in
some way 'belong' together, for example the different source files of a
program or all files about .... (whatever you want). What makes this window
extra convenient is that the full path name is also saved in this list. So
all you have to do is click on the file you want to open and click on the
'Open' button (a double click will have the same effect).

 This window also has a pull-down window. Please be aware that the items in
the 'Project' menu are meant for the list of files. The items in the 'File'
menu are meant for the selected file. And the items in the 'Editor' menu
have nothing to do with the list of files, but can be used to start or open
a new file that is not in the list of files.

 @{u}Gadget         Function                                                    @{uu}
 @{b}Projects@{ub}       (This is the left listview) Here you can select a project.
 @{b}Load@{ub}           Load a previously saved project. (With filerequester).
 @{b}Save@{ub}           Save the selected project. (With filerequester).
 @{b}New@{ub}            Create a new project. (With filerequester).
 @{b}Close@{ub}          This closes the selected project.

 @{b}Source Files@{ub}   Here you see the list of files in the selected project, the
                type of the file and the status are also displayed.
 @{b}Add@{ub}            Add a file to the list of files.
 @{b}Delete@{ub}         Remove the selected file from the list.
 @{b}Move up@{ub}        Move the selected file one place up in the list.
 @{b}Move down@{ub}      Move the selected file one place down in the list.
 @{b}Open@{ub}           Open the selected file.
 @{b}Close@{ub}          Close the selected file.
 @{b}Hide@{ub}           Hide the selected file (the editor window will be closed,
                but the file will remain in memory).
 @{b}Reveal@{ub}         Reveal the selected file (Reveal = 'unhide').


@endnode
@node "WindowManager" "'Window Manager' window"

 The 'Window Manager' window shows a list of all files that are loaded in
the memory. The status of each file is also display, this can be either
'Opened' or 'Hidden'.

 @{u}Gadget         Function                                                    @{uu}
 @{b}Windows@{ub}        The list of files currently in memory.
 @{b}Close@{ub}          Close the selected file (and window).
 @{b}Hide@{ub}           Hide the selected file (the editor window will be closed,
                but the file will remain in memory).
 @{b}Reveal@{ub}         Reveal the selected file (Reveal = 'unhide').

@endnode
@node "Toolbar" "'Toolbar...' window"

 The 'Toolbar...' window can be used to change the toolbar of the editor
windows (for more information about this toolbar see @{"Editor" LINK Editor}).

 @{u}Gadget         Function                                                    @{uu}
 @{b}Icons@{ub}          A list of all available buttons.
 @{b}Toolbar@{ub}        The list of buttons in the toolbar.
 @{b}>>@{ub}             Copy the selected icon to the toolbar list.
 @{b}<<@{ub}             Remove the selected button from the toolbar list.
 @{b}Move up@{ub}        Move the selected button one place up in the toolbar list.
 @{b}Move down@{ub}      Move the selected button one place down in the toolbar list.
 @{b}Ok@{ub}             Close this window.
 @{b}Save@{ub}           Save the new toolbar settings in a separate file. If you
                want these settings to be saved as the default use the
                'Save settings' item from the 'Settings' menu.
 @{b}Load@{ub}           Load the toolbar settings from a preference file, this can
                either be a file previously saved with the 'Save' button or
                a complete settings file (only toolbar settings will be
                loaded).

@endnode
@node "Editor..." "'Editor...' window"

 The 'Editor...' window can be used to change the editor settings that apply
to all editor windows.

 @{u}Gadget         Function                                                    @{uu}
 @{b}Tab size@{ub}       The default tab size for a new editor window. (See also
                @{"Statistics" LINK Statistics}).
 @{b}Buffer size@{ub}    The size of the text buffer for a new editor window (every
                time the buffer is full a new (bigger) one has to be
                allocated which may slow down editing). 4096 is a nice
                setting.
 @{b}End of line@{ub}    What should the cursor do at the end of the line when you
                press the right arrow key ? 'Stop' will stop the cursor,
                'Move on' will move the cursor further to the right
                (although there is no more text there) and 'To next line'
                will wrap the cursor to the next line.
 @{b}AutoSave@{ub}       'On' will automatically save your file after some time
                (counting from the first change you made). 'Off' will
                prevent this, 'Ask' will display a requester instead of
                saving it directly.
 @{b}AutoSave Time@{ub}  The time between the first change and the moment of the
                AutoSave.
 @{b}Max undo level@{ub}	The maximal number of undo's in memory (more undo's will
                take more memory and slow down the system a little).
 @{b}Wordwrap@{ub}       At what cursor position should AmisED 'see' the end of the
 @{b}column@{ub}         line ? 0 means this function is inactive.
 @{b}Codebar height@{ub} This is the amount of lines the codebar should display.
 @{b}Flashing curs.@{ub}	Flash the cursor instead of a cursor that is always visible.
 @{b}Auto-Indent@{ub}    This will move the cursor to the position under the first
                character (that is not a space or tab) on the previous line
                when you press enter.
 @{b}Wordwrap@{ub}       This will activate wordrapping at the end of a line.
 @{b}Cursor Up/Down@{ub} This will move the cursor back to the end of the
 @{b}Wrap@{ub}           line if the cursor is behind the end of the line when you
                move the cursor up or down.
 @{b}Fast mode@{ub}      Everything will be displayed in black and gray, this will
                speed up the graphical routines like scrolling and
                redrawing.
 @{b}Create backups@{ub} AmisED now saves an extra backup file of the document you
                save.
 @{b}Create icons@{ub}   Save icons with your files (if the file doesn't have an own
                icon the icon 'def_text.info' from the drawer 'ENV:AMIS'
                will be used).
 @{b}Enable numeric@{ub} Now you are able to use functions like 'Page down/up' and
 @{b}keypad@{ub}         'Home' via the numeric keypad.
 @{b}Automatic@{ub}      AmisED will not ask to switch to the appropriate viewer
 @{b}viewer@{ub}         anymore, but will act immediately.
 @{b}switching@{ub}
 @{b}Insert tab as@{ub}  Use spaces instead of real tabs.
 @{b}spaces@{ub}
 @{b}Toolbar@{ub}        Indicates wether or not the toolbar should be ON or OFF when
                you open a new editor window.
 @{b}Viewerbar@{ub}      Indicates wether or not the viewerbar should be ON or OFF
                when you open a new editor window.
 @{b}Statusbar@{ub}      Indicates wether or not the statusbar should be ON or OFF
                when you open a new editor window.
 @{b}Codebar@{ub}        Indicates wether or not the codebar should be ON or OFF when
                you open a new editor window.
 @{b}Ok@{ub}             Close this window.
 @{b}Save@{ub}           Save the new editor settings in a separate file. If you want
                these settings to be saved as the default use the
                'Save settings' item from the 'Settings' menu.
 @{b}Load@{ub}           Load the editor settings from a preference file, this can
                either be a file previously saved with the 'Save' button or
                a complete settings file (only editor settings will be
                loaded).

@endnode
@node "SmartIndent" "'Smart Indent...' window"

 The 'Smart Indent...' window can be used to define words or characters
which should cause an indent. For example in a C source code you might want
to indent automatically after a '{' character, this can be set in this
window.

 @{u}Gadget         Function                                                    @{uu}
 @{b}[Upper cycle]@{ub}  Selects the viewer/editor module for which you want to
                change the smart indent settings.
 @{b}[Listview]@{ub}     A list of the defined strings to be recognized.
 @{b}Add@{ub}            Add a string to the indent list.
 @{b}Remove@{ub}         Remove the selected string from the indent list.
 @{b}Move up@{ub}        Move the selected string one place up in the indent list.
 @{b}Move down@{ub}      Move the selected string one place down in the indent list.
 @{b}Position@{ub}       Where in the line should the string be found.
 @{b}Line to indent@{ub}	Which line should be indented.
 @{b}Direction@{ub}      Should that line be indented one step forward or backward.
 @{b}Allow multiple@{ub}	Should AmisED indent more steps if the string was found
                several times.
 @{b}Type@{ub}           Should the indent be done with tabs or spaces.
 @{b}Ok@{ub}             Close this window.
 @{b}Save@{ub}           Save the new smart indent settings in a separate file. If
                you want these settings to be saved as the default use the
                'Save settings' item from the 'Settings' menu.
 @{b}Load@{ub}           Load the smart indent settings from a preference file, this
                can either be a file previously saved with the 'Save'
                button or a complete settings file (only smart indent
                settings will be loaded).

@endnode
@node "CurrentWindow" "'Current window settings...' window"

 The 'Current window settings...' window can be used to change some settings
for only the selected editor window.

 @{u}Gadget         Function                                                    @{uu}
 @{b}Current window@{ub}	Display's the name of the window of which the settings can
                now be changed.
 @{b}Font@{ub}           With this gadget you can change the font to be used for
                displaying your text.
 @{b}Tab size@{ub}       Change the tab size.
 @{b}Ok@{ub}             Close this window.
 @{b}Next@{ub}           Select the next editor window.
 @{b}Prev@{ub}           Select the previous editor window.

@endnode
@node "Screen" "'Screen...' window"

 The 'Screen...' window can be used to change the screen AmisED should use.

 @{u}Gadget         Function                                                    @{uu}
 @{b}Screen mode...@{ub}	Change the screen mode of the screen AmisED should open.
 @{b}On pubscreen@{ub}   The name of the public screen AmisED should open upon
                (No name indicates the default public screen, usualy this is
                the Workbench).
 @{b}Own screen@{ub}     AmisED should open an own screen.
 @{b}Clone Workb@{ub}    Use the screen mode, palette, etc. from the workbench
                screen.
 @{b}Ok@{ub}             Close this window.
 @{b}Apply@{ub}          Applies the current settings to the current AmisED screen.
 @{b}Save@{ub}           Save the new screen settings in a separate file. If you want
                these settings to be saved as the default use the
                'Save settings' item from the 'Settings' menu.
 @{b}Load@{ub}           Load the screen settings from a preference file, this can
                either be a file previously saved with the 'Save' button or
                a complete settings file (only screen settings will be
                loaded).

@endnode
@node "Palette..." "'Palette...' window"

 The 'Palette...' window can be used to change the colors used by AmisED.

 @{u}Gadget         Function                                                    @{uu}
 @{b}Base colors@{ub}    The colors used by AmisED for the GUI etc.
 @{b}ANSI colors@{ub}    The standard ANSI colors.
 @{b}ANSI Shine col@{ub}	The colors used by AmisED for bold text in ANSI files when
                Bold=Shine is selected in the @{"Editor..." LINK Editor...} settings window.
 @{b}Force colors@{ub}   AmisED will now ignore locks on the current palette colours.
 @{b}to change@{ub}      Programmes running on the AmisED public screen are forced to
                change colours too.
 @{b}Upper slider@{ub}   Changes the red value of the selected color.
 @{b}Mid slider@{ub}     Changes the green value of the selected color.
 @{b}Lower slider@{ub}   Changes the blue value of the selected color.
 @{b}Ok@{ub}             Close this window.
 @{b}Save@{ub}           Save the new palette settings in a separate file. If you want
                these settings to be saved as the default use the
                'Save settings' item from the 'Settings' menu.
 @{b}Load@{ub}           Load the palette settings from a preference file, this can
                either be a file previously saved with the 'Save' button or
                a complete settings file (only palette settings will be
                loaded).

@endnode
@node "DefaultFonts" "'Default fonts...' window"

 The 'Default fonts...' window can be used to tell AmisED which font is to
be used for the different viewers.

 @{u}Gadget         Function                                                    @{uu}
 @{b}Normal@{ub}         Change the default font for the normal viewer.
 @{b}ANSI@{ub}           Change the default font for the ANSI viewer.
 @{b}AmigaGuide@{ub}     Change the default font for the AmigaGuide viewer.
 @{b}Ok@{ub}             Close this window.
 @{b}Save@{ub}           Save the new font settings in a separate file. If you want
                these settings to be saved as the default use the
                'Save settings' item from the 'Settings' menu.
 @{b}Load@{ub}           Load the font settings from a preference file, this can
                either be a file previously saved with the 'Save' button or
                a complete settings file (only palette settings will be
                loaded).

@endnode
@node "Keyboard..." "'Keyboard...' window"

 The 'Keyboard...' window can be used to change the functions assigned to a
key.

 @{u}Gadget         Function                                                    @{uu}
 @{b}Cycle@{ub}          This cycle gadget shows the keyboard settings for the
                different viewers available.
 @{b}Change@{ub}         Change the selected key to an other key or key-combination,
                the functions assigned to it will stay the same.
 @{b}Add@{ub}            Add a key or key-combination you want to give a special
                function.
 @{b}Remove@{ub}         Remove the selected key from the list.
 @{b}Edit@{ub}           Edit the commands assigned to the selected key, to do this
                you will get an '@{"Edit commands..." LINK Editcommands}' window.
 @{b}Sort@{ub}           Sort the key list.
 @{b}Default Keys@{ub}   - Not implemented in version 1.03 -
 @{b}Ok@{ub}             Close this window.
 @{b}Save@{ub}           Save the new keyboard settings in a separate file. If you
                want this settings to be saved as the default use the
                'Save settings' item from the 'Settings' menu.
 @{b}Load@{ub}           Load the keyboard settings from a preference file, this can
                either be a file previously saved with the 'Save' button, or
                a complete settings file (only keyboard settings will be
                loaded).

@endnode
@node "Menu..." "'Menu...' window"

 The 'Menu...' window can be used to change to pull-down menu of the editor
windows.

 @{u}Gadget         Function                                                    @{uu}
 @{b}Menus@{ub}          A list of the menus in the pull-down menu.
 @{b}Items@{ub}          A list of the menu items in the selected menu.
 @{b}Sub items@{ub}      A list of the sub items in the selected menu item.
 @{b}Add (3x)@{ub}       Add a menu / menu item / sub item to the list.
 @{b}Remove (3x)@{ub}    Remove the selected menu / menu item / sub item from the
                list.
 @{b}Move up (3x)@{ub}   Move the selected menu / menu item / sub item one place up
                in the list.
 @{b}Move down (3x)@{ub}	Move the selected menu / menu item / sub item one place down
                in the list.
 @{b}Edit@{ub}           Edit the commands assigned to the selected menu item / sub
                item.
 @{b}A-Key@{ub}          Assign an Amiga-... short-cut to the selected menu item /
                sub item.
 @{b}Barlabel@{ub}       Change the selected menu item / sub item to a barlabel.
 @{b}Subs@{ub}           Indicate that the selected menu item has some sub items.
 @{b}Ok@{ub}             Close this window.
 @{b}Save@{ub}           Save the new menu settings in a separate file. If you want
                this settings to be saved as the default use the
                'Save settings' item from the 'Settings' menu.
 @{b}Load@{ub}           Load the menu settings from a preference file, this can
                either be a file previously saved with the 'Save' button, or
                a complete settings file (only menu settings will be
                loaded).

@endnode
@node "Programming..." "'Programming' window"

 The 'Programming...' window can be used to change the settings for the
compile, assemble, link and debug functions.

 @{u}Gadget         Function                                                    @{uu}
 @{b}Compiler draw.@{ub}	The directory AmisED should go to before executing the
                compile command.
 @{b}Compiler comm.@{ub}	The command AmisED should execute when a compile command
                was given.
 @{b}Precompile@{ub}     An Arexx script AmisED executes when compilation is
 @{b}script@{ub}         activated.
 @{b}PostCompile@{ub}    An Arexx script AmisED executes after compilation is ready.
 @{b}script@{ub}
 @{b}Assembler draw.@{ub}The directory AmisED should go to before executing the
                assemble command.
 @{b}Assembler comm.@{ub}The command AmisED should execute when a assemble command
                was given.
 @{b}Linker draw.@{ub}   The directory AmisED should go to before executing the link
                command.
 @{b}Linker comm.@{ub}   The command AmisED should execute when a link command was
                given.
 @{b}C-Debug. draw.@{ub}	The directory AmisED should go to before executing the
                C-debug command.
 @{b}C-Debug. comm.@{ub}	The command AmisED should execute when a debug command was
                given (on a file with a name indicating that it is a C
                source code).
 @{b}A-Debug. draw.@{ub}	The directory AmisED should go to before executing the
                ASM-debug command.
 @{b}A-Debug. comm.@{ub}	The command AmisED should execute when a debug command was
                given (on a file with a name indicating that it is a ASM
                source code).
 @{b}Use text draw.@{ub}	Indicate that AmisED should go to the directory where the
        @{b}(5x)@{ub}    source was saved before executing the command displayed left
                from this gadget.
 @{b}Use own proc.@{ub}  Indicate that AmisED should detach this program (otherwise
        @{b}(5x)@{ub}    AmisED will wait until it returned).
 @{b}Ok@{ub}             Close this window.
 @{b}Save@{ub}           Save the new programming settings in a separate file. If you
                want this settings to be saved as the default use the
                'Save settings' item from the 'Settings' menu.
 @{b}Load@{ub}           Load the programming settings from a preference file, this
                can either be a file previously saved with the 'Save'
                button, or a complete settings file (only programming
                settings will be loaded).

@endnode
@node "Miscellaneous..." "'Miscellaneous...' window"

 The 'Miscellaneous...' window can be used to change the settings for the
startup script.

 @{u}Gadget         Function                                                    @{uu}
 @{b}Startup script@{ub}	The filename of the script to be execute when AmisED is
                booting up. (This must be an ARexx script).
 @{b}CON Window@{ub}     The so called 'CON' window which AmisED uses to open the
                shell for example.
 @{b}Ok@{ub}             Close this window.
 @{b}Save@{ub}           Save the new miscellaneous settings in a separate file. If
                you want this settings to be saved as the default use the
                'Save settings' item from the 'Settings' menu.
 @{b}Load@{ub}           Load the miscellaneous settings from a preference file, this
                can either be a file previously saved with the 'Save'
                button, or a complete settings file (only miscellaneous
                settings will be loaded).

@endnode
@node "Internalcommand" "'Internal command...' window"

 The 'Internal command...' window can be used to give AmisED an internal
command (for a full list see @{"Internal Commands" LINK Internal_Commands}).

 @{u}Gadget         Function                                                    @{uu}
 @{b}Command string@{ub}	The command you want AmisED to execute.
 @{b}? (the upper)@{ub}  Shows a list of all available internal commands.
 @{b}Syntax@{ub}         Shows the arguments you can give to the selected command.
 @{b}? (the lower)@{ub}  Shows the help text in this file about the selected command.
 @{b}Result@{ub}         The result that the command returned (after you pressed
                'Ok').
 @{b}Ok@{ub}             Execute the command.
 @{b}Cancel@{ub}         Close this window.

@endnode
@node "Executecommand" "'Execute Command...' window"

 The 'Execute Command...' window can be used to run an AmigaDOS command from
within AmisED.

 @{u}Gadget         Function                                                    @{uu}
 @{b}Command string@{ub}	The command you want to execute.
 @{b}[Filereq]@{ub}      Select a command from a filerequester.
 @{b}Ok@{ub}             Execute the selected command (it will be detached so you can
                continue working with AmisED while the command is being
                executed).
 @{b}Cancel@{ub}         Close this window.

@endnode
@node "Editcommands" "'Edit commands...' window"

 The 'Edit commands...' window can be used to change a list of command from
a key-definition, a macro or a menu definition. (For more information about
the commands you can use see @{"Internal Commands" LINK Internal_Commands}).

 @{u}Gadget         Function                                                    @{uu}
 @{b}Editing@{ub}        The key, macro or menu the list of commands is assigned to.
 @{b}Command list@{ub}   The list of commands.
 @{b}[String gadget]@{ub}The selected command.
 @{b}? (The upper)@{ub}  Shows a list of all available internal commands.
 @{b}[Text gadget]@{ub}  Shows the arguments you can give to the selected command.
 @{b}? (The lower)@{ub}  Shows the help text in this file about the selected command.
 @{b}Add@{ub}            Add a command to the command list.
 @{b}Remove@{ub}         Remove the selected command from the command list.
 @{b}Move up@{ub}        Move the selected command one place up in the command list.
 @{b}Move down@{ub}      Move the selected command one place down in the command
                list.
 @{b}Optimize@{ub}       Optimize the command list (this is very useful to speed up
                macro's, just try it and you will see).
 @{b}Ok@{ub}             Close this window.

@endnode
@node "Getting_Started" "Getting started"

 If you start AmisED as you find it after using the 'Install' script, AmisED
will open with an empty editor window. Here you can type your text and edit
it using the menus.

 You can get this help file using the 'Help' option in the 'Misc' menu,
pressing 'Amiga-H' or the help-key. You can customize AmisED using the
options in the 'Settings' menu. Most special functions are easily available
by menu and/or toolbar. The best way to find out what is possible is just
try all the different menu options and buttons.

@endnode
@node "Saver" "Save your files after a failure"

 Although AmisED has been tested quite a lot, there might still be some bugs
in it. If you are editing a file and after a while, for some reason, AmisED
isn't responding any more, you can still save your file!!

 This can be done with a very special feature of AmisED. When you start
AmisED, it will look for an other AmisED that might already be running. If
there is an other AmisED it will be signalled to show a requester asking the
user wether or not he wants to start a new copy of AmisED. If the other
AmisED is not responding to this signal, the new copy will start up. Then it
will ask the user if he wants to add the files that were opened in the other
AmisED to the file list of the new AmisED. If so, the files will be
available via the 'Window Manager' (this might not work when to much data
was damaged, in that case your files are lost!). Now you can access the
files by just 'revealing' them.

@endnode
