@node "COM_Iconify" "Internal command: Iconify"

        @{fg shine}Iconify@{fg text}

@{b}Function:@{ub}       This function will iconify AmisED, all windows and the
                AmisED screen will be closed. You can reopen AmisED with a
                double click on the AppIcon on the workbench. (@{fg shine}Warning:@{fg text} If
                you use to much memory when AmisED is iconified you might
                not be able to reopen the AmisED enviroment!).
@{b}Syntax:@{ub}         -
@{b}Result:@{ub}         0  - Ok.
                10 - Failed.

@{b}Options:@{ub}        -

@endnode
@node "COM_Quit" "Internal command: Quit"

        @{fg shine}Quit@{fg text}

@{b}Function:@{ub}       Quit AmisED.
@{b}Syntax:@{ub}         FORCE/S
@{b}Result:@{ub}         0  - Ok.

@{b}Options:@{ub}        FORCE:  Quit without the usual quit requester.

@endnode
@node "COM_ResultToVar" "Internal command: ResultToVar"

        @{fg shine}ResultToVar@{fg text}

@{b}Function:@{ub}       This function allows you to use the result of a previous
                internal command as a variable for the next internal
                command.
@{b}Syntax:@{ub}         VAR/N
@{b}Result:@{ub}         Always the same as the previous command, this has no special
                meaning.

@{b}Options:@{ub}        VAR:    Here you must give the number of the variable of
                        the next command were the result should be used.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        'Request BODY="Enter a number" LONG'
                        The result will be the number the user entered.
                'ResultToVar VAR=3'
                        3 Because 'ASCII=...' is the 3th option of the
                        'Insert' command.
                'Insert'
                        This will insert a character with the ASCII code the
                        user entered in the requester!

@endnode
@node "COM_Help" "Internal command: Help"

        @{fg shine}Help@{fg text}

@{b}Function:@{ub}       Show the on-line help guide (this file).
@{b}Syntax:@{ub}         -
@{b}Result:@{ub}         0  - Ok.

@{b}Options:@{ub}        -

@endnode
@node "COM_Graphics" "Internal command: Graphics"

        @{fg shine}Graphics@{fg text}

@{b}Function:@{ub}       Switch off graphical routines. This is very useful for
                macro's, they will be executed much faster because not all
                steps are displayed. You MUST turn it back on when you are
                done, otherwise the user won't see any changes.
@{b}Syntax:@{ub}         ON/S,OFF/S
@{b}Result:@{ub}         0  - Ok.

@{b}Options:@{ub}        ON:     Switch graphical routines on.
                OFF:    Switch graphical routines off.

@endnode
@node "COM_Fold" "Internal Command: Fold"

        @{fg shine}Fold@{fg text}

@{b}Function:@{ub}       This function is used to 'fold' a part of a text. This
                means that some lines are made invisible to make the
                structure of the text more clear. For example in AmigaGuide
                mode this function will hide all lines of a node (page), it
                only leaves the title visible.
@{b}Syntax:@{ub}         TOGGLE/S,ALL/S
@{b}Result:@{ub}         0  - Ok.
                10 - Viewer doesn't support folding.

@{b}Options:@{ub}        TOGGLE: Toggle between folded and unfolded text.
                ALL:    Fold (or toggle) all parts of the text that can be
                        folded.

@endnode
@node "COM_UnFold" "Internal Command: UnFold"

        @{fg shine}UnFold@{fg text}

@{b}Function:@{ub}       This function is used to 'unfold' a part of a text. For more
                information about folding see @{"Fold" LINK COM_Fold}.
@{b}Syntax:@{ub}         ALL/S
@{b}Result:@{ub}         0  - Ok.
                10 - Viewer doesn't support folding.

@{b}Options:@{ub}        ALL:    UnFold all parts of the text that are currently
                        folded.

@endnode
@node "COM_Print" "Internal Command: Print"

        @{fg shine}Print@{fg text}

@{b}Function:@{ub}       Print the current tekst.
@{b}Syntax:@{ub}         -
@{b}Results:@{ub}        0  - Ok.

@endnode
@node "AmigaDOS_Arguments" "AmigaDOS Arguments"

 All internal commands work with the standard AmigaDOS template functions,
this means that arguments should be givin in the same way as for normal DOS
commands.

 There are several argument types. In the template string (syntax string)
the type of the argument is indicated with these characters:

 \N     This is a number.
 \K     This is a text.
 \S     This is a switch.

 \A     This argument must always be given.

 For strings there are some extra things you should know. If you want to
insert spaces in a string you should quote the string with " characters. For
example: TEXT="A test" (A test). If you want to use " characters in the
string you should give *" instead. For example: TEXT="*"A test*"" ("A test").
If you want to use a * character in the string you should give ** instead.
For example: TEXT="** A test **" (* A test *).
                
@endnode
